#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

int missingNumber(std::vector<int>& nums) {
    std::sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());

    for (int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
        if (nums[i] != i)        // value should equal index if nothing is missing
            return i;
    }

    return nums.size();          // missing number is n (the last one)
}

int main() {
    std::vector<int> nums = {0, 2, 3, 1, 4};
    std::cout << "Missing number: " << missingNumber(nums) << std::endl; // 5
    return 0;
}
```

---

## How it works

After sorting, the array **should look like `[0, 1, 2, 3, ...]`** — every value should match its index. The first place where `nums[i] != i` is the gap.
```
Sorted: [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]
Index:   0  1  2  3  4

nums[0] == 0  ✓
nums[1] == 1  ✓
nums[2] == 2  ✓
nums[3] == 3  ✓
nums[4] == 4  ✓

No mismatch found → missing number is n = 5  ✓
```

Another example with `[3, 0, 1]`:
```
Sorted: [0, 1, 3]
Index:   0  1  2

nums[0] == 0  ✓
nums[1] == 1  ✓
nums[2] == 3  ✗ → return index 2  ✓
